Description

The remote Windows host is missing security update 5062552. It is, therefore, affected by multiple vulnerabilities



  - Buffer over-read in Windows TDX.sys allows an authorized attacker to elevate privileges locally.

    (CVE-2025-49659)



  - Improper link resolution before file access ('link following') in Windows Update Service allows an authorized attacker to elevate privileges locally. (CVE-2025-48799)



  - Improper link resolution before file access ('link following') in Windows AppX Deployment Service allows an authorized attacker to elevate privileges locally. (CVE-2025-48820)



Solution

Apply Security Update 5062552

Pete

Hi Graham,


Alpesh has advised me to contact you regarding this ticket raised by Dan.

Dan asked us to look into getting his device up and running after experiencing the "Blue Screen of Death". After almost an hour of troubleshooting, we managed to confirm, using the diagnostics mode, that the device is not recognising the hard drive as being connected anymore. Dan advised me that he is unable to make it into the office for a replacement now and has put forward the possibility of purchasing a device to be used for work applications. The device would need to be configured remotely by us to install our remote management software, and to install any managed FPB applications necessary.
I have advised Dan to look into some HP devices to ensure uniformity among the FPB managed devices, minimising the possibility of application incompatibility.


I could not find anything in our knowledgebase to indicate that there is a specific process for device purchasing/configuration in extenuating circumstances such as this, so please let me know if you're happy to proceed, or if there were another path that you would like to take to ensure that Dan is able to continue working as soon as possible.

Hi Team,

Can the following devices please be patched with the updated version, as outlined below?

172.29.120.129
kd-syd-32
172.20.3.254
kd-syd-50

Description
The version of Microsoft Edge installed on the remote Windows host is prior to 138.0.3351.109. It is, therefore, affected by multiple vulnerabilities as referenced in the July 25, 2025 advisory.

  - Type Confusion in V8 in Google Chrome prior to 138.0.7204.168 allowed a remote attacker to potentially exploit heap corruption via a crafted HTML page. (Chromium security severity: High) (CVE-2025-8010, CVE-2025-8011)

Solution
Upgrade to Microsoft Edge version 138.0.3351.109 or later.

Thanks
Pete

Detail of the logged fault
Orro Group has published an informational cyber security advisory regarding four critical zero-day VMware vulnerabilities affecting ESXi, Workstation, Fusion, Tools, and Cloud Foundation. These vulnerabilities allow virtual machine (VM) escape, host-level code execution, and memory leakage. Exploitation requires administrative access within a guest VM, and is particularly critical in multi-tenant or service provider environments. Three of the patched flaws have a severity rating of 9.3, allowing programs running in a guest virtual machine to execute commands on the host. The vulnerabilities are identified as CVE-2025-41236, CVE-2025-41237, CVE-2025-41238, and CVE-2025-41239. Affected products include VMware ESXi, VMware Workstation 17.x, VMware Fusion 13.x, VMware Tools (11.x.x to 13.x.x), and VMware Cloud Foundation. No workarounds are available, and remediation steps include applying patches or upgrading to the latest supported versions of affected products, prioritizing immediate action for environments with active VMXNET3, VMCI, or PVSCSI usage, and limiting admin access on guest VMs while auditing virtual hardware configurations.

  - Buffer over-read in Windows TDX.sys allows an authorized attacker to elevate privileges locally. (CVE-2025-49659)



  - Improper link resolution before file access ('link following') in Windows Update Service allows an authorized attacker to elevate privileges locally. (CVE-2025-48799)



  - Improper link resolution before file access ('link following') in Windows AppX Deployment Service allows an authorized attacker to elevate privileges locally. (CVE-2025-48820)



Solution

Apply Security Update 5062554.

Hi Shani,

Good day,

Here are the steps on how to add the email address in Safe sender.

Classic Outlook (Windows Desktop App)

  1. Open Outlook.
  2. Go to the Home tab.
  3. Click Junk > Junk E-mail Options.
  4. Select the Safe Senders tab.
  5. Click Add.
  6. Enter the email address (e.g., someone@example.com) or domain (e.g., @example.com).
  7. Click OK, then Apply and OK again.

New Outlook

  1. Open the New Outlook interface.
  2. Click the Settings gear icon (top right).
  3. Select Mail > Junk email.
  4. Under Safe senders and domains, click Add.
  5. Type the email address or domain.
  6. Click Save.

Outlook Web App (OWA)

  1. Go to Outlook Web.
  2. Click the Settings gear icon > View all Outlook settings.
  3. Navigate to Mail > Junk email.
  4. Under Safe senders and domains, click Add.
  5. Enter the email address or domain.
  6. Click Save.


Please let me know if you have further questions for this one.


Thank you

Exploitation requires administrative access within a guest VM, which is particularly critical in multi-tenant or service provider environments. The vulnerabilities are tracked under CVE-2025-41236, CVE-2025-41237, CVE-2025-41238, and CVE-2025-41239. Three of these flaws have a severity rating of 9.3, allowing programs running in a guest VM to execute commands on the host. Affected products include various versions of VMware ESXi, VMware Workstation 17.x, VMware Fusion 13.x, VMware Tools (11.x.x to 13.x.x), and VMware Cloud Foundation. No workarounds are available, and remediation includes applying patches or upgrading to the latest supported versions of affected products. Immediate action should be prioritized for environments with active VMXNET3, VMCI, or PVSCSI usage. Limiting admin access on guest VMs and auditing virtual hardware configurations is also recommended. For more details, please refer to the provided advisory links.

Hi Helton,

Thanks for your patience while this ticket has been in our escalation queue.

Looking at the Defender framework and how specific URLs / domains can be whitelisted, there's a very specific limitation that's been affecting the rules we're attempting to impose.

Originally, we were assigning Paul's device to a second group targeting dropbox.com specifically for whitelisting, however this group was not applying as expected. What we found is that Defender now has a limitation where it will only assign a single group per device, and only to the group with the highest priority in the group list. As Paul's device is already part of the 'Google Docs Exception' group, it will not register as belong to the 'Dropbox Exception' group we created.

My only real option to get around this restriction is to whitelist dropbox.com for the existing 'Google Docs Exception' group. This group consists of devices belonging to:

Angela Smith
Caroline Radowski
Paul Wallwork

If you're happy to allow Dropbox access for all three users I can have the rule activated almost immediately.

The version of Microsoft Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL2) on the remote Windows host is prior to 2.5.10. It is, therefore, affected by a kernel elevation of privilege vulnerability:

Upgrade to Microsoft Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL2) version 2.5.10 or later.

Summary
[OrroCyber #313223] [Informational] Orro Group Cyber Security Advisory - Cisco Identity Services Engine Unauthenticated Remote Code Execution Vulnerabilities

Detail of the logged fault
Orro Group has recently published an informational cyber security advisory regarding two critical remote code execution vulnerabilities in Cisco Identity Services Engine (ISE) and ISE-Passive Identity Connector (ISE-PIC), identified as CVE-2025-20281 and CVE-2025-20282. Both have the maximum CVSS base score of 10. These vulnerabilities allow an unauthenticated, remote attacker to issue commands on the underlying operating system as the root user. Proof of concept exploit code is publicly available. Affected versions include Cisco ISE and ISE-PIC releases 3.3 and 3.4. From:  Automation via RT<mss-plena@cyber.orro.group>
Subject: [OrroCyber #319777] Advisory - Multiple vulnerabilities affecting NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway devices


Hello,

Orro Group has recently published an informational cyber security advisory.

Overview

Citrix have identified critical vulnerabilities in Citrix Netscaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway Products - CVE-2025-5349, CVE-2025-6543, CVE-2025-5775, CVE-2025-5776, CVE-2025-5777 and CVE-20258424.

CVE-2025-6543 is being actively exploited as a zero-day. Evidence strongly suggests CVE-2025-7775 ,CVE-2025-7776, CVE-2025-5777 and CVE-2025-8424 are also being actively exploited.

All vulnerable systems should be patched as a priority, as these products are high-value targets and previous vulnerabilities have been aggressively exploited.

Details

CVSS v4.0 Base Score: 9.2       CVSS:4.0/CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:H/AT:P/PR:N/UI:N/VC:H/VI:H/VA:H/SC:L/SI:L/SA:L
CVE-2025-5776<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-5776__;!!Omhi3nY!ipfZeBRvt8eH5UnBE5XeuAwez40J03eFd-EVE2wC2pxyS0I9DNLJtDXnAQeU14ePSKWCV3B0wSe2uuHDsuTpdnLV2IExlaGs$> Memory overflow vulnerability leading to unpredictable or erroneous behaviour and Denial of Service. CVE-2025-5777<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-5777__;!!Omhi3nY!ipfZeBRvt8eH5UnBE5XeuAwez40J03eFd-EVE2wC2pxyS0I9DNLJtDXnAQeU14ePSKWCV3B0wSe2uuHDsuTpdnLV2KGibboi$> Insufficient input validation leading to memory overread, potentially leading to the exposure of sensitive data.        CVSS v4.0 Base Score: 9.3       CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:L/AT:N/PR:N/UI:N/VC:H/VI:H/VA:H/SC:L/SI:L/SA:L
CVE-2025-6543<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-6543__;!!Omhi3nY!ipfZeBRvt8eH5UnBE5XeuAwez40J03eFd-EVE2wC2pxyS0I9DNLJtDXnAQeU14ePSKWCV3B0wSe2uuHDsuTpdnLV2ErAU_FT$> Memory overflow vulnerability leading to unintended control flow and Denial of Service  CVSS v4.0 Base Score: 9.2       CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:H/AT:P/PR:N/UI:N/VC:H/VI:H/VA:H/SC:L/SI:L/SA:L
CVE-2025-8424<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-8424__;!!Omhi3nY!ipfZeBRvt8eH5UnBE5XeuAwez40J03eFd-EVE2wC2pxyS0I9DNLJtDXnAQeU14ePSKWCV3B0wSe2uuHDsuTpdnLV2CdTifCJ$> Improper access control on the NetScaler Management Interface.  CVSS v4.0 Base Score: 8.7       CVSS:4.0/AV:A/AC:L/AT:N/PR:N/UI:N/VC:H/VI:H/VA:H/SC:L/SI:L/SA:L
Affected Products

CVE-2025-5777 and CVE-2025-5349

  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway 14.1-43.56 and later releases
  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway 13.1-58.32 and later releases of 13.1
  *   NetScaler ADC 13.1-FIPS and 13.1-NDcPP 13.1-37.235 and later releases of 13.1-FIPS and 13.1-NDcPP
  *   NetScaler ADC 12.1-FIPS 12.1-55.328 and later releases of 12.1-FIPS

CVE-2025-6543

  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway 14.1 BEFORE 14.1-47.46
  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway 13.1 BEFORE 13.1-59.19
  *   NetScaler ADC 13.1-FIPS and NDcPP BEFORE 13.1-37.236-FIPS and NDcPP

CVE-2025-5775, CVE-2025-5776 and CVE-2025-8424

  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway?14.1?BEFORE 14.1-47.48
  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway?13.1?BEFORE 13.1-59.22
  *   NetScaler ADC 13.1-FIPS and NDcPP BEFORE 13.1-37.241-FIPS and NDcPP
  *   NetScaler ADC 12.1-FIPS and NDcPP BEFORE 12.1-55.330-FIPS and NDcPP

NOTE: Citrix advises that NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway versions 12.1 and 13.0 are now End Of Life (EOL) and not receiving patches.

Remediation

Upgrade to the latest available versions, or at least the following:

  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway 14.1-47.46 and later releases
  *   NetScaler ADC and NetScaler Gateway 13.1-59.19 and later releases of 13.1
  *   NetScaler ADC 12.1-FIPS 12.1-55.328 and later releases of 12.1-FIPS
  *   NetScaler ADC 13.1-FIPS and 13.1-NDcPP 13.1-37.236 and later releases of 13.1-FIPS and 13.1-NDcPP

Customers should contact support - https://support.citrix.com/support-home/home<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://support.citrix.com/support-home/home__;!!Omhi3nY!ipfZeBRvt8eH5UnBE5XeuAwez40J03eFd-EVE2wC2pxyS0I9DNLJtDXnAQeU14ePSKWCV3B0wSe2uuHDsuTpdnLV2LLRlFCo$> to obtain the 13.1-FIPS and 13.1-NDcPP builds that address this issue.

The vendor recommends clearing all sessions post-upgrade, via the following commands:


kill icaconnection -all
kill pcoipConnection -all

If using the Outlook app (iOS/Android):

  1. Open the Outlook app.

  2. Go to Settings (gear icon) → tap your work account.

  3. Turn on Save Contacts (iOS) or Sync Contacts (Android).

    • This will push your Outlook/Exchange contacts into your phone’s native Contacts app.

If using the built-in Mail/Exchange account:

  1. Go to your phone Settings → Accounts → Work/Exchange account.

  2. Make sure Contacts sync is enabled.

    • On iPhone: Settings → Mail → Accounts → choose your work account → enable Contacts.

    • On Android: Settings → Accounts → Exchange/Work → Account sync → turn on Contacts.

COMMUNICATION:

What happened?

Between 13:43 UTC and 14:19 UTC on 20 September 2025, a platform issue resulted in an impact to Virtual Machines in Australian East. During the incident, customers may have experienced packet loss, which could have caused application disconnections and failures in any operation (such as create, read, update, or delete) performed on Azure Virtual Machines in the region; affected operations should have succeeded upon retry, and no customer data loss occurred.


What went wrong, and why?

During the impact window, a limited number of customers may have experienced degraded performance due to the failure of a network device at the data center, resulting in packet loss for traffic passing through that device. These errors resulted in temporary availability drops, which led to an increase in failures for operation requests for resources leveraged in the region.


How did we respond?

  *   13:45 UTC on 20 September 2025 - Customer impact began. Established monitors detected an increase in failure rates for operations, which triggered an alert and prompted us to investigate this event.
  *   14:00 UTC on 20 September 2025 - Based on our analysis of error logs, we were able to correlate the increase in failures to a backend system that was experiencing availability issues due to a faulty network device.
  *   14:10 UTC on 20 September 2025 - To mitigate this issue, we isolated the faulty network device from production.
  *   14:19 UTC on 20 September 2025 - After a period of monitoring, we concluded that full-service functionality was restored, the traffic was restored to the region, and we declared mitigation.


What happens next?
